<br>
the following image was generated with gnuplot, the data is from a logfile i forgot i left on, stretching from level 55 to nearly level 58.  this is all activity in that range, raids included, str from 180-255, dex from 100-180, various ranger ATK buffs sometimes, so on so forth.  it is my unfounded suspicion that these buffs raise the &quot;average ocurring minimum&quot; on the modal (eg DB + (DI * (10..20)) is more common than DB + (DI * (1..10)), and a model of 10 exactly is the most frequent).<br>
<br>
i wrote a quick awk script which produced the frequency of times i hit for each amount.  then used gnuplot to produce a graph.  on the X axis you'll see an amount I hit for.  on the Y axis you'll see the number of times i hit (anything) for that amount.  the results are not as evenly distributed as one might have thought.<br>
<br>
the slash data includes both a Short Sword of the Morning and the paladin Epic, Fiery Defender.<br>
<br>
the pierce data is /only/ a 30/37 velium type lance, which is what i used when i didn't need to bash prior to getting epic.<br>
<br>
the 'all' data is the sum of the two, it seemed useful at the time, but clearly isn't.<br>
<br>
the resulting area under the graph reveals that i'm a paladin.  film at 11.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.mercenary.net/LoadedDice.gif"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
you can see how the slash data is basically comprised of 2 sets of data organized similarly to the pierce data.  this makes the pierce data the most useful for visualizing individual hit distribution.<br>
<br>
so, paying attention to only the pierce data, note the 4 discrete zones produced.<br>
<br>
1) the preamble, a relatively large spike at what we calculate is the weapon's minimum damage.  i seem to recall some patch message ages ago that said we'd hit for minimum more often than missing now.  rounding up the not-quite-zeroes, i guess.<br>
<br>
2) the loading sawtooth.  randonmess isn't, very.  it seems either odd or even modals are statistically less likely.  i'm too lazy to figure out which.  note that the slope is 'generally up' and then 'flattens out' prior to the next zone.<br>
<br>
3) the average.  5,000 froglok scars agree, with any given weapon, if you hit, you're probably hitting for this number.<br>
<br>
4) the trailing slope.  a straight line (the jags in the graph in this area are too small to infer any meaning) down to your max.<br>
<br>
<br>
at any rate, i found it educationally amusing, since i was anticipating a bell curve.  i wasn't hoping to answer anything by posting, just offering a new avenue for someone more interested to continue. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ugimmelgreatheart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Gimmel Greatheart</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ckwmail.com/pictures/fologo.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/9/02 5:05:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1242.topic&index=83>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.artemisgames.com/images/gimmel1trans.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ubermob tanking</span><hr size=1> Somethings that could still use looking at I think:<br>
