Take Z times the range, Z*20 = 8. Assume this value is your modal on the bell curve of X probability, ...<br>
<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The problem with this theory is that it doesn't produce anything like the damage histograms seen from players.<br>
<br>
I haven't seen a damage histogram from a mob, but I would bet my epic it looks something like:<br>
<br>
- a spike at DB + DI<br>
<br>
- equal value peaks at DB + 2 DI, DB + 3 DI, ... , DB + 19 DI<br>
<br>
- a spike at DB + 20 DI<br>
<br>
This is the same as that of a level 1 PC, who doesn't get any bonus hits - I guess mobs lack the stats or skills needed to get those.<br>
<br>
What mitigation AC does is change the relative height of the two spikes, and the flat area between them.<br>
<br>
For the fungus beast example posted earlier, we have DB = 31, DI = 5.<br>
<br>
If you have extremely high mitigation, you might get 5% chance of a normal hit, 5% chance of a max hit, and 90% chance of a min hit.<br>
<br>
That would lead to an average damage per hit of 43.<br>
<br>
With very low mitigation, you might get 5% chance of a normal hit, 5% chance of a minimum hit, and 90% chance of a max hit.<br>
<br>
That would lead to an average damage per hit of 123.<br>
<br>
Soru<br>
