<br>
As a note on avoidance vs mitigation AC.If we were to test a level x Warrior with full armour on (non-stat giving) and then with no armour on versus the same mob and the results were to show that mitigation was affected but avoidance was not then we can imply from this that armour has no (or an insignificantly small) effect on the probability of avoiding a mobs blow.<br>
<br>
HOWEVER, we can NOT imply from this that {Mitigation AC = Naked AC} and therefore {Total AC - Naked AC = Mitigation AC}.<br>
<br>
The reason being that: a) Naked AC may be completely Mitigation AC still and therefore Avoidance AC may simply not be shown at all in the visible AC stats or; b) Naked AC may be a combination of both Mitigation and Avoidance AC. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/usylphan2.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sylphan2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are Superior</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/12/02 9:49:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1242.topic&index=99>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Hey Gjin...</span><hr size=1> Here is a very abbreviated version of the AC formula that's useful for this discussion.<br>
<br>
For War, Pal, SK, Dru, Clr, Shm, Brd, Rog, Ran (but not Monk), the formula is:<br>
<br>
Avoidance = A + (D * 16/9)<br>
Mitigation =  (B/4) + (D/3) + (E * 4/3)<br>
Displayed AC = (Avoidance + Mitigation) * 1000/847<br>
where<br>
A = a factor based on agility, ranges from approx. -24 to 75.<br>
B = AC from buffs.  Inspect the spellfile for details.  Skin Like Nature for example adds 55.<br>
D = your Defense skill<br>
E = equipment AC.  Add up the ACs of all equipment worn.<br>
<br>
It's all done with integers -- truncate the fractions at every point possible.<br>
<br>
Can I prove it?  Almost... proved it all except I'm not sure whether the (D/3) factor should be in avoidance or mitigation, or maybe it's a third, seperate, factor.  For casters the avoidance is the same but the mitigation uses different divisors.  That's why I've assumed the (D/3) is part of mitigation, because it's also different for casters.  Monks... well, monks are all screwed up by that weight limit thing.<br>
